 {"id":"bd-gw1u","title":"CRITICAL: Implement keep-alive timeout in HTTP server","description":"The HTTP server has keep-alive enabled but no timeout mechanism. Connections can be held indefinitely, causing resource exhaustion in production. Must implement timeout using asupersync Budget.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:49:02.008830899Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-28T03:25:05.648748285Z","closed_at":"2026-01-28T03:24:58.709044670Z","close_reason":"Implemented keep-alive timeout: added KeepAliveTimeout error variant, read_with_timeout function with deadline-based polling, tests for timeout behavior","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-gw1u","depends_on_id":"bd-51xl","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-01-28T02:55:54.987771790Z","created_by":"ubuntu"}],"comments":[{"id":5,"issue_id":"bd-gw1u","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"## Background & Context
The HTTP server in fastapi-http implements keep-alive (persistent connections) but lacks timeout handling. Per HTTP/1.1 spec, servers should close idle connections after a reasonable timeout to prevent resource exhaustion.

## Current Implementation
In crates/fastapi-http/src/lib.rs:
- Server accepts connections and processes requests in a loop
- keep_alive_enabled flag exists
- NO timeout mechanism for idle connections
- Connections can be held open indefinitely

## Security & Production Impact
1. **Resource Exhaustion**: Malicious clients can open thousands of connections and hold them, exhausting server file descriptors
2. **Slowloris Attack Vector**: Attackers can send partial requests slowly to tie up connections
3. **Memory Pressure**: Each connection consumes memory for buffers
4. **Production Blocker**: Cannot deploy to production without connection timeouts

## Solution Architecture

### Using asupersync Budget
asupersync provides Budget for structured timeouts:
```rust
use asupersync::{Budget, Cx};

async fn handle_connection(cx: &Cx, stream: TcpStream) {
    let idle_budget = cx.budget(Duration::from_secs(30));

    loop {
        // Wait for next request with timeout
        match idle_budget.timeout(read_request(&stream)).await {
            Ok(Some(req)) => {
                // Reset idle timer for keep-alive
                idle_budget.reset();
                handle_request(cx, req).await;
            }
            Ok(None) => break, // Connection closed
            Err(BudgetExhausted) => {
                // Idle timeout - close connection gracefully
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Configuration
```rust
pub struct ServerConfig {
    pub keep_alive_timeout: Duration,  // Default: 30s
    pub request_timeout: Duration,     // Default: 60s
    pub connection_limit: usize,       // Default: 1024
}
```

## Files to Modify
1. crates/fastapi-http/src/lib.rs - Server struct, connection handling
2. crates/fastapi-http/src/config.rs - Add ServerConfig (may need to create)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Idle connections are closed after configurable timeout (default 30s)
- [ ] Request processing has separate timeout (default 60s)
- [ ] Timeout uses asupersync Budget (not tokio::time)
- [ ] Graceful connection close (send Connection: close header)
- [ ] Tests verify timeout behavior
- [ ] Benchmark shows no regression for normal traffic

## Dependencies
- Requires asupersync Budget API to be available
- Should coordinate with connection draining (fastapi_rust-fac)

## Test Plan
1. Unit test: Connection closes after idle timeout
2. Unit test: Active request not interrupted by idle timeout
3. Integration test: Slowloris-style attack is mitigated
4. Benchmark: Verify no performance regression

## Considerations
- Timeout granularity: Too short = premature closes, too long = resource waste
- HTTP/2 has different keep-alive semantics (PING frames) - future consideration
- Load balancers may have their own timeouts - document interaction
